(a) Normalized Operating Cash Flow: Earnings before interest, depreciation, amortization and any activities that are not repeatable business functions, after reinvestement of maintenance.
(b) Weighted Importance: The relative importance given to each year in the cash flow normalization process.
(c) Normalized Weighted Operating Cash Flow: The sum of the product of each normalized operating cash flow by the weighted importance given to each period.
(d) Characteristic Cash Flow: Representative cash flow for valuation purposes.
(e) Capitalized Characteristic Cash Flow: The quotient of the representative cash flow by the capitalization rate.
(f) Excess (Insufficiancy) Working Capital: The excess of current assets over a factor of current liabilities required to maintain operating activities. By default the factor is set to 1.2 but might be different from one industry to another.
(g) Excess Assets: The value of assets not required for current operations, including investments and discontinued operations. By default, they constitute of investments and discontinued operations.
(h) Unrealized Capital Gain On Real Estate, Net Of Taxes: The non-materialized capital gain on assets that is not reflected in the costs and amortized costs of the financial statements.
(i) Present Value Of Tax Protection: Present value of future tax benefits. For reasons of availability of information, the present value of tax protection is valued at half the net deferred tax asset (liability).
(j) Business Value: Value of the company's total assets.
(k) Long-Term Debt And Operating Lease Obligations: The value of amounts due long-term to contributors of funds who are not shareholders of the company.
(l) Value Of All Category Of Shares: The net asset value of the company.
(m) Value Accruing To Preferred Shareholders: The amount that would have to be paid to reimburse the preferred shareholders in full.
(n) Common Shares Fair Value: Net asset value after considreation of value accruing to preferred and minority shareholders.
(o) Fair Value Of Identifiable Assets: The sum of commercial value of each asset that could be separetely disposed of.
(p) Goodwill Fair Value: Excess of intrinsic value over the fair value of net identifiable assets.

(a) Normalized Income: Earnings before interest and after any activities that are not repeatable business functions.
(b) Weighted Importance: The relative importance given to each year in the net income before interest normalization process.
(c) Normalized Weighted Income Before Interest: The sum of the product of each normalized net income before interest by the weighted importance given to each period.
(d) Characteristic Income Before Interest: Representative net income for valuation purposes.
(e) Capitalized Characteristic Income Before Interest: The quotient of the representative net income by the capitalization rate.
(f) Excess (Insufficiancy) Working Capital: The excess of current assets over a factor of current liabilities required to maintain operating activities. By default the factor is set to 1.2 but might be different from one industry to another.
(g) Excess Assets: The value of assets not required for current operations, including investments and discontinued operations.
(h) Unrealized Capital Gain On Real Estate, Net Of Taxes: The non-materialized capital gain on assets that is not reflected in the costs and amortized costs of the financial statements.
(i) Present Value Of Tax Protection: Present value of future tax benefits. For reasons of availability of information, the present value of tax protection is valued at half the net deferred tax asset (liability).
(j) Business Value: Value of the company's total assets.
(k) Long-Term Debt And Operating Lease Obligations: The value of amounts due long-term to contributors of funds who are not shareholders of the company.
(l) Value Of All Category Of Shares: The net asset value of the company.
(m) Value Accruing To Preferred Shareholders: The amount that would have to be paid to reimburse the preferred shareholders in full.
(n) Common Shares Fair Value: Net asset value after considreation of value accruing to preferred and minority shareholders.
(o) Fair Value Of Identifiable Assets: The sum of commercial value of each asset that could be separetely disposed of.
(p) Goodwill Fair Value: Excess of intrinsic value over the fair value of net identifiable assets.

(a) Total Assets Expected Return: Target return on all assets before factoring risk, growth and cost of financing otherwise accruing to common shareholders. By default, the expected return has been fixed to 4%. What is essential here is comparability.
(b) Weighted Cost Of Total Assets: The average rate the company pays to all security holders to finance the total assets.
(c) Risk Related To Volatility Of Return On Total Assets: Standard deviation arising from the difference between return on total assets over the past five years and the average return on total assets for those same five years. Captures the risk that the yield will vary in the future based on past volatility.
(d) Expected Decline (Expected Growth): Average gross margin growth over the past three years.
(e) Cost Of Total Assets Accruing To Common Shares Shareholders: The part of the cost of total assets attributable non controlling interests and preferred sharesholders see Additional Information for normalization purposes.
(f) Growth Related Risk Provision: With respect to the Capitalization Rate Floor from Additional Information Tab.
(g) Capitalization Rate: The rate used to determine the multiple of characteristic or expected profit or cash flows. As default, the minimum value is 2.1% any additional growth results in an equivalent additional risk of volatility on total assets.

(a) Price / Earnings: The price-earnings ratio (P/E ratio) relates a company's share price to its earnings per share. A high P/E ratio could mean that a company's Share is over-valued, or else that investors are expecting high growth rates in the future.
(b) Market / Book: The Market to Book ratio (also called the Price to Book ratio), is a financial valuation metric used to evaluate a company’s current market value relative to its book value. The market value is the current share price of all outstanding shares (i.e. the price that the market believes the company is worth).
(c) Return on Equity: The return on equity (ROE) is a measure of the profitability of a business in relation to the equity. Because shareholder's equity can be calculated by taking all assets and subtracting all liabilities, ROE can also be thought of as a return on assets minus liabilities. ROE measures how many dollars of profit are generated for each dollar of shareholder's equity. ROE is a metric of how well the company utilizes its equity to generate profits.
(d) Return on Assets: Return on Assets (ROA) is an indicator of how well a company utilizes its assets, by determining how profitable a company is relative to its total assets. ROA is best used when comparing similar companies or comparing a company to its previous performance.
(e) Profit Margin: Profit margin refers to the revenue a company makes after paying COGS. The profit margin is calculated by taking revenue minus the cost of goods sold. However, the difference is shown as a percentage of revenue. The percentage of revenue that is gross profit is found by dividing the gross profit by revenue.
(f) Operating Margin: Operating profit margin is a profitability ratio that investors and analysts use to evaluate a company's ability to turn a dollar of revenue into a dollar of profit after accounting for expenses. In other words, operating margin is the percentage of revenue left over after accounting for expenses.
(g) Dividend Payments: The dividend payout ratio is the ratio of the total amount of dividends paid out to shareholders relative to the net income of the company. It is the percentage of earnings paid to shareholders in dividends. The amount that is not paid to shareholders is retained by the company to pay off debt or to reinvest in core operations.
(h) Earnings Retention: The retention ratio is the portion of earnings kept back in a firm to grow the business as opposed to being paid out as dividends to shareholders. The payout ratio is the opposite of the retention ratio which measures the percentage of profits paid out as dividends to shareholders.
(i) Basic Earning Power: The Basics Earning Power Formula The Basic Earning Power (BEP) Formula, which is also referred to as the Basic Earning Power Ratio, is as follows: Basic Earning Power = Earnings Before Interest and Taxes (EBIT)/Total Assets
(j) Debt-To-Equity: The debt-to-equity (D/E) ratio is calculated by dividing a company’s total liabilities by its shareholder equity. These numbers are available on the balance sheet of a company’s financial statements. The ratio is used to evaluate a company's financial leverage. The D/E ratio is an important metric used in corporate finance.
(k) Equity Multiplier: The equity multiplier is a risk indicator that measures the portion of a company’s assets that is financed by shareholders' equity rather than by debt. It is calculated by dividing a company's total asset value by its total shareholders' equity.
(l) DuPont: The DuPont analysis (also known as the DuPont identity or DuPont model) is a framework for analyzing fundamental performance popularized by the DuPont Corporation. DuPont analysis is a useful technique used to decompose the different drivers of return on equity (ROE). The decomposition of ROE allows investors to focus on the key metrics of financial performance individually to identify strengths and weaknesses.
(m) Degree Of Financial Leverage: A degree of financial leverage (DFL) is a leverage ratio that measures the sensitivity of a company’s earnings per share (EPS) to fluctuations in its operating income, as a result of changes in its capital structure. The degree of financial leverage (DFL) measures the percentage change in EPS for a unit change in operating income, also known as earnings before interest and taxes (EBIT).
(n) Debt-To-EBITDA: The net debt-to- EBITDA (earnings before interest depreciation and amortization) ratio is a measurement of leverage, calculated as a company's interest-bearing liabilities minus cash or cash equivalents, divided by its EBITDA.
(o) Interest Coverage: The interest coverage ratio is a debt ratio and profitability ratio used to determine how easily a company can pay interest on its outstanding debt. The interest coverage ratio may be calculated by dividing a company's earnings before interest and taxes (EBIT) by its interest expense during a given period by the company's interest payments due within the same period.
(p) Fixed-Charge Coverage: The fixed-charge coverage ratio (FCCR) shows how well a company's earnings can be used to cover its fixed charges such as rent, utilities, and debt payments. Lenders often use the fixed-charge coverage ratio to assess a company's overall creditworthiness.
(q) Liquidity Current: The current ratio is a liquidity ratio that measures a company's ability to pay short-term obligations or those due within one year. It tells investors and analysts how a company can maximize the current assets on its balance sheet to satisfy its current debt and other payables.
(r) Liquidity Quick: Quick liquidity ratio is the total amount of a company’s quick assets divided by the sum of its net liabilities and its reinsurance liabilities. Quick assets are liquid assets such as cash, short-term investments, equities, and corporate and government bonds nearing maturity.
(s) Inventory Turnover: The inventory turnover ratio is an effective measure of how well a company is turning its inventory into sales. The ratio also shows how well management is managing the costs associated with inventory and whether they're buying too much inventory or too little. Additionally, inventory turnover shows how well the company sells its goods.
(t) Days Of Inventory On Hand: Days’ Inventory on Hand Ratio Days’ inventory on hand (also called days’ sales in inventory or simply days of inventory) is an accounting ratio which measures the number of days a company takes to sell its average balance of inventory. It is also an estimate of the number of days for which the average balance of inventory will be sufficient.
(u) Number Of Days Payable: Days payable outstanding (DPO) is a financial ratio that indicates the average time (in days) that a company takes to pay its bills and invoices to its trade creditors, which may include suppliers, vendors, or financiers. The ratio is typically calculated on a quarterly or annual basis, and indicates how well the company’s cash outflows are being managed.
(v) Fixed Assets Turnover: The fixed asset turnover ratio (FAT) is, in general, used by analysts to measure operating performance. This efficiency ratio compares net sales (income statement) to fixed assets (balance sheet) and measures a company's ability to generate net sales from its fixed-asset investments, namely property, plant, and equipment (PP&E).
(w) Total Asset Turnover: Asset turnover is the ratio of total sales or revenue to average assets. This metric helps investors understand how effectively companies are using their assets to generate sales. Investors use the asset turnover ratio to compare similar companies in the same sector or group.
Definitions from Investopedia.

(a) Target Working Capital: For the purpose of computing the Excess (Insufficiant) Working Capital (Capitalized Cash Flow & Capitalized Income calculations).
(b) Reinvestment Of Maintenance: Average payments to acquire property, plant and equipments (by default, it's the last six years average).
(c) Theorical Interest Charge: 3.5% of debt, borrowings and obligations. We consider that any reduction from 3.5% would result in an external risk factor due to economic instability.
(d) Theorical Tax Rate: Tax charge for the year, provided that it is in the range of 15 and 30%. Anything lower would result in risk for tax positions and dependence on a jurisdiction. Anything higher is deemed attributable to the volatility of the effective tax rate between periods.
(e) Dividend Payment To Non Controlling Interests: Dividend payment to other than common shareholders are to be added back in the calculation of your cost of total assets for the purpose of finding your capitalization rate.
(f) Dividend Payment To Preferred Shareholders': Id.
(g) Total Assets Expected Return: Target return on all assets before factoring risk, growth and cost of financing otherwise accruing to common shareholders. By default, the expected return has been fixed to 4%. What is essential here is comparability.
(h) Capitalization Rate Floor: Lowest capitalization rate deemed reasonable.

Mission
USERS
Users of the web application range from business and portfolio managers, valuators, risk managers, brokers, financial advisors and others. As the application is made available to anyone who wishes to consult the database, the users are essentially made up of the public at large.
TYPE OF AUDIT
Data Processing Internal Audit
NEEDS OF USERS
Users need Financial Statements exempt from material misstatements in order to conduct various analysis aimed at evaluating the entity's financial performance, understanding its financial and cost structure, making investment decisions and implementing appropriate strategies with full knowledge of the underlying circumstances.
SCOPE
{{ entity.lastyear }} and the five years before
RISK
The financial information obtained from the Security and Exchange Commission has already been duly audited. The main risk factor therefore lies in the collection and compilation of this data.
STRATEGY
Given the nature of the mission, only corroboration procedures can be carried out. The main objective is to ensure the completeness and accuracy of the data.
